3 Introduction

This notebook is thought as a working document for the development and documentation of the FS20C3 - Datenjournalismus project).

AidData is a research lab at William & Marys Global Research Institute. AidDatas interdisciplinary team focus on research and analysis of development investments from more than 90 grants and contracts worth more than $50 million over the last 16 years. Taking as starting point the data provided by them and after a previous research about media use of the information gathered and made available to the public by this organization, weve developed a new data-driven story. In order to do that, data from the core dataset were selected, extracted and analysed to built our written and visual narrative.

The data-driven story we want to tell with the help of the data provided by AidData, is about the successfull and quick development of a national water supply and sanitation net that Vietnam has accomplished in the past two decades. This huge progress has been possible thanks, among other reasons, to a broad international cooperation. In this notebook weve dug into the available data to bring into the light the main protagonists of this collaborative achievement and try to picture the time line that makes it a today reality.

With this in mind, weve looked for the 3-digit sector classification based on OECD purpose codes that comes in the documentation of the data and selected the activities that are related to our main goal.

4 Data Importing

The core dataset provided by AidData can be found here. This dataset tracks known international development flows from bilateral and multilateral aid organizations from 1947 to 2013 in a flat-table structure. Information available are served as a granular data from more level of details to a general overview. After getting a first impression of the different datasets that encompass the whole data core and reading the documentation, we end that the information we need for our story is located in the thin version (more than 1.500.000 entries).

5 Data Pre-Processing

In this step we are going to transform our imported data in a way that allows us to apply further analysis. Typically, this process requires some data wrangling, data transformation and the creation of new variables.

# The 3-digit sector classification based on OECD purpose codes tells us that
# codes beginning with 140 corresponds to Water Supply and Sanitation.
# Among the different activities in this category:
# - Water Supply and Sanitation, combination of purposes (14000)
# - Water Supply and Sanitation, purpose unspecified or does not fit under any other applicable codes (14005)
# - Basic drinking water supply and basic sanitation (14030) 
# - Waste management/disposal (14050)
# - Education and training in water supply and sanitation (14081) 

# Select columns and rows we are interesting in with values different as nas.
codes <- c(14000, 14005, 14030, 14050, 14081)
years <- 1992:2013
(head(df1 <- df_full %>%
  select(3:8) %>%
  filter((recipient == "Viet Nam" | recipient == "Bangladesh") & (year %in% years) & coalesced_purpose_code %in% codes) %>% # Subjects of our analysis are Viet Nam and Bangladesh
  na.omit()))

Looking at our first preliminary summarized results for the variable amount, we can see that surprisingly, among the more frequent donors, just Japan (30.0146%) stays in the podium as the most generous contributors. The other two, Germany (3.7103%) and UNICEF (0.4945%), are down (7 Germany) or far down (18 UNICEF) the list. Just as we saw before, together the three main donors (1 Japan, 2 IDA and 3 ASDB) regarding the amount of money theyve given in the past two decades to Vietnam and Bangladesh, represents a vast proportion of the total amount of money given adding up to 58.507%. Another thing that catched our eye was the huge difference between max and min values. Lets take our main contributor, Japan, as example. The maximum amount of money that country has given to our both analysed recipients was 341355248 USD, while the minimum was just 113 USD. A 385731430.24% more!

The total amount both countries has received from the 31 donors during the period that goes from 1992 to 2013 (dataset) was 3031258034 USD.
